    <title>Combined summary - Stumbling into a contentious soft fork activation attempt</title>
    <updated>2023-06-15T15:06:19.424977+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2022-January/019730.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In various Bitcoin developer mailing lists and forums, there have been discussions about the proposed opcode OP_CTV that enables covenants on Bitcoin. Some developers express concerns about the lack of sufficient scrutiny and research on the long-term implications of the proposal. Skepticism is also raised regarding the readiness of OP_CTV to be activated as a consensus change, with some arguing that more work needs to be done to ensure its safety and utility. Additionally, there are debates about the potential harm or benefits of expanding use-cases in Bitcoin, with some arguing that fees will be the incentives for miners as subsidy decreases, while others question the need for separate soft forks if the implementation is ready in a few months. Overall, these discussions highlight the importance of careful consideration and testing before implementing significant changes to the Bitcoin protocol.The conversation revolves around the proposed implementation of OP_CTV in Bitcoin and the need for a separate soft fork for it. There is discussion about the danger of a contentious soft fork activation attempt and the lack of work on the speculated use cases of OP_CTV. Prayank is an active participant in the discussion and is currently reviewing pull request 21702 and creating contracts using Sapio for OP_CTV. Michael Folkson expresses skepticism about rushing through the implementation of covenants without sufficient research. There is also a discussion about BIP 118, SIGHASH_ANYPREVOUT, which explores the use case of eltoo payment channels. Lastly, Jeremy Rubin expressed gratitude for his review and feedback of the Bitcoin Improvement Proposals (BIPs) and sought guidance on best practices for linking to BIPs and implementations given the need to rebase and respond to feedback with changes.The discussion among Bitcoin developers is centered on the proposed implementation of OP_CTV, a consensus change in Bitcoin that enables covenants. While some individuals believe it is ready to go in a few months, others argue that more review and testing are necessary before attempting an activation. The priority should be to avoid rushing through a change without sufficient research and community support. Skeptics are calling for a higher bar on readiness for consensus changes and encourage proponents of OP_CTV to explore alternative proposals and thoroughly examine its use cases. In contrast, the authors and contributors of another soft fork proposal, BIP 118, are building out and testing one of the speculated use cases, eltoo payment channels. In various discussions, concerns have been raised regarding the potential harm of expanding use-cases for on-chain transactions in Bitcoin. It is argued that such expansions could lead to a contentious blocksize debate and compete with existing users for scarce blockchain space. Additionally, there is a need for compelling use-cases that are beneficial to all users, rather than just a small subset. The invocation of Satoshi's opinions in present-day discussions has also been a point of contention, with some arguing that his opinions remain relevant while others argue that he is no longer involved in Bitcoin development. In email conversations, Prayank and ZmnSCPxj disagreed over the relevance of Satoshi's opinions. Meanwhile, discussions were had over whether Bitcoin should be scaled rapidly or not, with some arguing that delaying scaling would harm Bitcoin's growth while others question the notion that the Lightning Network is the primary cause of recent low fees. Overall, any core consensus changes to the almost $1 trillion dollar system must be carefully weighed against the risks.Lastly, the context discusses the potential harm of expanding use-cases for on-chain transactions in Bitcoin. It is noted that there are issues with covenants, but CHECKTEMPLATEVERIFY approaches are restricted to simple templates, limiting potential risks. Safety concerns are raised regarding templated transactions as they could expand in an infinitely long number of steps, making it difficult for practical purposes. Testing for these transactions is poorly documented without clear goals regarding edge cases being tested. Prayank shares compelling use cases for Bitcoin in an email communication with Peter, who argues that some of the use cases mentioned in the links could harm all users. Peter emphasizes the need to carefully weigh the benefits and risks of making core consensus changes to Bitcoin. The discussion also touches on the need for compelling use-cases that are clearly beneficial to all users. Finally, ZmnSCPxj objected to the invocation of Satoshi in regards to Bitcoin development, stating that if he wants to participate in Bitcoin development today, he can speak for himself.</summary>
